I revisited this issue today as it occurred to me while finishing up our user-interface (file uploader/manager) that if a user deletes a file created by the snowball import (where empty objects were &#39;not&#39; created representing any directories delimited in the Key name), if it is the last object representing a given directory structure, that directory structure essentially ceases to exist!

I did some testing using the SDK and confirmed my suspicions. If I create an empty object to represent the directory then create an object within it, deleting the object does not delete the directory represented by the empty object with a trailing delimiter. But if I create an object without creating an empty &#39;directory&#39; object first, deleting that object removes any evidence that the &#39;directory path&#39; ever existed.

I also confirmed that  you can create the &#39;empty&#39; directory representation after the fact it will not effect any objects containing the [pseudo] directory in it&#39;s key name. But deleting all objects containing that &#39;path&#39; will not remove the existence of the directory.

So it seems, either I have to create a work-around in any and all &#39;delete&#39; functions that will check if it contains a &#39;directory&#39; representation and create an empty object representing it&#39;s folder if it does not already exist before deleting the object, or I am going to have to go through the entire system and create empty objects for any and all objects that appear to be in &#39;folders&#39; as a result of their keyname.

Ugh, it would be nice if AWS documented this somewhere. I don&#39;t immediately see anything in the snowball documentation that makes it clear this is the case.

A few other ramifications of this:

It is possible to create an object representing a file in a [pseudo] directory such as:

    myfolder/path/myfile.txt

Then create another object that appears to use the same name as a folder:

    myfolder/path/myfile.txt/anotherfile.txt

It is even possible to create a [pseudo]directory placeholder&quot;

    myfolder/path/myfile.txt/


It should also be noted that since the directories do not actually exist (unless you create a placeholder to represent their existence) that if you have a long path represented in an object key, such as:

    some/really/long/path/myfile.txt

That the following &#39;directories&#39; don&#39;t actually exist if you do not implicitly create them:

    some/
    some/really/
    some/really/long/
    some/really/long/path/

Which means if you delete that object, any trace of those &#39;directories&#39; without placeholders (or other objects representing the same pseudo-path) cease to exist!

It should also be noted that if you wanted to delete anything represented as a sub path of that pseudo-tree, such as deleting everything under &quot;some/really/*&quot; you would have to use the utility SDK function: deleteMatchingObjects with the prefix &quot;some/really&quot;* or &quot;some/really/&quot; or an equivalent regex. Just doing a &#39;deleteObject&quot; for &quot;some/really/&quot; will only remove any existing placeholder with the key &quot;some/really&quot; and won&#39;t track down and remove files such as the example above.

NOTE: the &quot;some/really&quot; without the trailing slash might match other files such as &quot;some/reallybig.jpg&quot;

SW

Addendum:
Rather than going through the entire bucket creating placeholders for every pseudo-directory represented in a key name, I realized the only time it will be a potential problem is when deleting an object that includes in it&#39;s key name the representation of a path. If I then test and create an &#39;parent&#39; directory whenever an object with a key representing a file in a sub-directory, I can preserve the emulation of those folders, as trying to delete the &#39;parent&#39; created when an object was deleted will then test and create any additional parents until no more parent directories are represented in the key &#39;path&#39;.

the below function allows you to pass the original key, then uses a regex to find any sub directories (assumes a unix &#39;forward slash&#39; delimiter):

    /**
     * run prior to a delete to preserve any directories represented in the
     *   pathname due to the &#39;flat&#39; nature of the S3 filesystem.
     * Checks if the &#39;key&#39; represents a file in a &#39;pseudo&#39; directory.
     *   If yes, it checks if an empty placeholder exists for the directory.
     *   If no, it creates one to preserve the directory in the bucket.
     * @param string $target
     * @param null|string $bucket
     * @return \Aws\Result|S3Exception|\Exception
     */
    private function _preDeletePersistSubdir($target, $bucket=null) {
        if(preg_match(&#39;#^([^/]+.*/)[^/]+/?$#&#39;, $target, $m)) {
            $subDir = $m[1];
            try {
                if((!$this-&gt;getS3ClientCached()-&gt;doesObjectExist($bucket,$subDir))) {
                    $params = array(
                        &quot;Bucket&quot; =&gt; $bucket,
                        &quot;Key&quot; =&gt; $subDir,
                        &quot;Body&quot; =&gt; &quot;&quot;
                    );
                    return $putDirResult = $this-&gt;getS3ClientCached()-&gt;putObject( $params );
                }
            } catch(S3Exception $e) { return $e; }
        }
    }

Similarly, you could recursively build the entire tree with a similar function changing the &#39;if&#39; on the preg_match to a &#39;while&#39; being sure to assign $target = $subDir at the end of each loop:


    /**
     * @param string $target
     * @param null|string $bucket
     * @return \Aws\Result|S3Exception|\Exception
     */
    private function createSubdirPlaceholders($target, $bucket=null) {
        while(preg_match(&#39;#^([^/]+.*/)[^/]+/?$#&#39;, $target, $m)) {
            $subDir = $m[1];
            try {
                if((!$this-&gt;getS3ClientCached()-&gt;doesObjectExist($bucket,$subDir))) {
                    $params = array(
                        &quot;Bucket&quot; =&gt; $bucket,
                        &quot;Key&quot; =&gt; $subDir,
                        &quot;Body&quot; =&gt; &quot;&quot;
                    );
                    return $putDirResult = $this-&gt;getS3ClientCached()-&gt;putObject( $params );
                }
            } catch(S3Exception $e) { return $e; }
            $target = $subDir;
        }
    }

